Cicero says that a debtor (qui debet) has what belongs to another, ‘ aes retinet alienum,' which may be said in a sense, as people sometimes say it now, but every ⁴body knows that it is false3 for a man who has borrowed a hundred pieces from an- other, and accordingly owes him a hun- dred pieces, is still only a debtor for a hun- dred pieces. Those which he has received as a loan become his own property, as the Roman lawyers tell us (Gaius, iii. 90), and as the law of all nations must allow. If a man returns a favour, he may still be grateful for it, or he ought to be. He returns in one sense, but he still has in another. The Roman language can express this, but we cannot. XVhen the Romans said that a man ⁴ aes retinet alienum,' they did not mean what the words literally expreSS. As already observed, a man who lends a sum of money, transfers the ownership of it. If he did not, he could claim back the very pieces of money. The change of ownership is the foundation of this action for his debt (condictio). Accordingly we have the clear definition of ‘aes alienum’ (Dig. 50. 16. 213) : “Aes alienum est quod nos aliis debemus ; aes suum est quod nobis debent :'' the first expresses our debts (passif), the second our credits (actif); or, as Savigny explains (System, &c., p. 514, note), ‘aes alienum . . . debomusss ⁴· that is to say, the money which has been transferred from the owncrship of another inan to our own, and which must go back again into the owner- ship of the former owner-‚⁰
